THIS WAS AN INTERVIEW WITH A MAN WHOSE LAST NAME WAS WILLIAMS BY STORYCORP.
WHEN THE SPEAKER WAS A YOUNG MAN HE USED TO THINK HIS FAMILY WAS RICH.
ONE DAY WHILE SITTING AT THE DINNER TABLE HE SAID SOMETHING LIKE "I'M SO GLAD WE'RE RICH" TO HIS PARENTS.
HIS MOTHER, PICTURED WEARING A DRESS AND A BEADED NECKLACE, SAID "WE'RE NOT EXACTLY RICH".
HIS FATHER, PICTURED AS A NARROW FACED MAN WITH CROOKED GLASSES SAID THEY WERE POOR.
ONE DAY THE FATHER WAS OFFERED A POSITION AS THE CUSTODIAN AT THE PUBLIC LIBRARY.
IN THOSE DAYS THE CUSTODIANS FOR PUBLIC BUILDINGS LIVED IN THE BUILDING.
THEY MOVED INTO THE APARTMENT ABOVE THE LIBRARY.
WHILE SOME LIBRARIES WEREN'T CLEAN, HIS FATHER'S WAS.
THE FLOORS WERE ALWAYS CLEAN AND WAXED, AND HE POLISHED THE TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES TOO SO THAT THEY GLEAMED.
YOU COULD SEE THE TOPS OF THE SHELVES AS YOU WENT UPSTAIRS.
YOU HAD TO BE QUIET, LIVING IN A LIBRARY, DURING THE DAY.
AT NIGHT THOUGH, NO ONE ELSE WAS IN THE BUILDING SO THE SPEAKER SAID HE COULD RUN AND YELL AS MUCH AS HE WANTED.
AND WHENEVER HE HAD A QUESTION ABOUT SOMETHING OR WAS CURIOUS HE WOULD GO DOWN TO THE LIBRARY FOR A BOOK AND READ UNTIL 3 IN THE MORNING.
HE SAID HE DIDN'T BRING FRIENDS HOME BECAUSE AT FIRST HE WAS ASHAMED, BECAUSE YOUNG KIDS ALWAYS WANT TO BE NORMAL.
HIS FRIENDS WOULD JOKE THAT "HE LIVES AT THE LIBRARY.
"NO, HE LITERALLY DOES LIVE AT THE LIBRARY".
HE SAID THAT LIVING IN THE LIBRARY GAVE HIM A THIRST FOR KNOWLEDGE, AND AS HE GREW OLDER HE CAME TO BE VERY GLAD HE LIVED THERE.
HE WAS THE FIRST MEMBER OF HIS FAMILY TO GRADUATE FROM HIGH SCHOOL, AND TO GO TO COLLEGE.
AT THE END OF THE STORY HE'S A PROFESSOR AT A UNIVERSITY.
HE BRINGS HIS FATHER TO SEE HIS CLASSROOM AND SHOWS HIM THE NAME PLATE WHICH CALLS HIM "PROFESSOR CLARK".
HE SAID HIS FATHER WAS QUIET, LIKE FATHERS ARE, BUT HE COULD TELL THE MAN WAS PROUD.
HE SAID HIS FATHER WANTED TO GIVE HIM BROADER HORIZONS THAN HE'D HAD, AND HAD DONE JUST THAT.
WHEN THE SPEAKER WAS A BOY HE THOUGHT HE WAS RICH.
HE TOLD HIS PARENTS ONE NIGHT THAT HE WAS GLAD THEY WERE RICH.
HIS MOTHER SAID THEY WEREN'T EXACTLY.
HIS FATHER SAID THEY WERE POOR.
ONE DAY THE BOY'S FATHER GOT HIRED TO WORK AS THE CUSTODIAN IN A PUBLIC LIBRARY.
IN THOSE DAYS, PEOPLE WHO WERE CUSTODIANS OF A BUILDING LIVED IN THAT BUILDING.
THE FAMILY MOVED INTO AN APARTMENT ABOVE THE LIBRARY.
THE BOY CALLED HIS FATHER THE KEEPER OF THE TEMPLE OF KNOWLEDGE.
HIS FATHER KEPT THE LIBRARY REALLY CLEAN, TOOK GOOD CARE OF IT UNLIKE SOME OTHERS.
HE WAXED THE TOPS OF THE BOOKSHELVES, SO WHEN YOU WENT UPSTAIRS YOU COULD SEE THE TOPS GLEAM.
DURING THE DAY THEY HAD TO BE QUIET, BUT AT NIGHT WHEN THERE WAS NO ONE ELSE AROUND THE BOY COULD RUN AND YELL AND PLAY.
WHENEVER HE WANTED TO KNOW SOMETHING HE WOULD GO AND GET A BOOK AND READ, OFTEN UNTIL 3AM.
HE NEVER BROUGHT HIS FRIENDS HOME, BECAUSE HE WAS EMBARASSED.
HE WAS AT AN AGE WHERE EVERYONE WANTED TO BE NORMAL.
HIS FRIENDS WOULD JOKE ABOUT HIM LIVING AT THE LIBRARY.
"NO, HE LITERALLY DOES LIVE AT THE LIBRARY!
BECAUSE HE LIVED THERE, HE DEVELOPED A GREAT THIRST FOR LEARNING.
HE WAS THE FIRST MEMBER OF HIS FAMILY TO FINISH HIGH SCHOOL, AND TO GRADUATE FROM COLLEGE.
HE BECAME A PROFESSOR AT A UNIVERSITY.
HE BROUGHT HIS FATHER TO SEE HIS NEW CLASSROOM, AND SHOWED HIM THE NAME PLACE THAT SAID "PROFESSOR CLARK".
HIS FATHER WAS QUIET, AS HE OFTEN WAS, BUT THE SPEAKER COULD TELL HIS FATHER WAS PROUD.
DAD HAD ALWAYS WANTED TO GIVE HIS SON BROADER HORIZENS, AND HAD DONE JUST THAT.
